<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-201-464  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 201 464.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 5 1990 v7 n9 p33(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DataClub gives Mac users open access to AppleTalk LANs.andO;(International Business Software Inc. to introduce DataClub forthe Macintosh connectivity software) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Higgins, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>International Business Software Inc announces DataClub for theMacintosh, a networking package that lets Macintosh users read,store, or modify files located anywhere on an AppleTalk LANwithout knowing exactly where they are placed.andP;  The programcombines peer-to-peer capabilities with support for server-basedfiles and uses the standard 'folder' directory structure in theMac interface.andP;  An optional security module lets the networkadministrator assign 'read only' privileges to files.andP;  DataClubfor the Macintosh will be available in Apr 1990 at $249 per user.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Software Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   DataClub for the Macintosh (Computer network software) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Local Area NetworksConnectivityResource SharingSoftware packagesProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steve HigginsandM;International Business Software Inc. will make its U.S.andP;  debut next monthwith networking software designed to tear down fences around Mac workstationsby giving users open access to files located anywhere on an AppleTalknetwork.andM;DataClub for the Macintosh lets Mac users read, alter or store existing ornew files to another workstation or server on the AppleTalk LAN withoutknowing its precise location.andP;  The software mirrors the peer-to-peernetworking capabilities found in Sun Microsystems Inc.'s TOPS networkingsoftware, but adds the ability for Mac users to access server-based files aswell as files stored on peer Mac workstations, said Nick Powell, president ofthe Sunnyvale, Calif., firm.andM;Optional software that enables PC workstations to share files on theAppleTalk network will also be available.andM;Networkwide file access is provided transparently within the standard Macinterface's &quot;folder&quot; structure.andP;  Users can access existing files by openingthe folder in which the files are stored.andP;  All files contained in thatlogical folder -- regardless of location -- are then available to the user,officials said.andP;  As such, users don't have to specify file locations and canaccess groups of files without switching from workstation to server drives orvice versa, officials said.andM;To safeguard against malicious use such a global-access system could lead to,an optional security module lets the system administrator assign &quot;read only&quot;rights to some files.andP;  The module also lets administrators specify thatcertain users can override and alter a file designated as read only.andM;DataClub for the Macintosh will be released at MacWorld in April for $249 peruser.andP;  The DataClub Security module will cost $249 per network.andP;  The DataClubServer and PC Gateway -- which provide access to Mac servers and enable PCusers to tap the network -- will be packaged together and priced at $499 pernetwork.andM;International Business Software can be reached at (408) 720-0170.andO;</TEXT></DOC>